<h1>2.3.3 3rd declension</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em>: add to discussion</p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>n</strong>
(noun)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> n-s—nn- (noun, singular,
neuter, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>The third declensional macroclass includes words whose stem ends in a
consonant, or the vowels ι or υ (or semivowels y or ϝ). All three
genders are present. The gen.sg has the ending -ος (-os). In theory, the
endings are the same for all words in this declension, but the
differences between stems final sound and the clash with the endings
cause e.g.&nbsp;assimilation and contraction, and the endings have some
variation. The differences are mostly apparent in the nominative
singular, accusative singular and dative plural. All other case endings
are quite effortlessly added to the stem.</p>
<p>The stem is most conveniently found from the <strong>gen.
sg.</strong> form by dropping the ending -ος (-os) (like the stem λιβ-
(lib-) from the noun ὁ λίψ gen. λιβ-ός (ho líps, gen. lib-ós)
<em>south</em>). For the 3rd declension tables
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.5" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.5">see Smyth
§240</a> and for the development and description of the macroclass, see
<span class="citation" data-cites="dresslerkatsouda2013">Dressler and
Katsouda (2013)</span>.</p>
