<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<ul>
<li>In accusative singular, it is often the case that writers add the
letter -ν (-n) to the ending -α (-a), as by analogy from the first
declension, e.g.&nbsp;γυναῖκαν (gunaîkan) instead of γυναῖκα (gunaîka)
<em>wife</em>, and θυγατέραν (thugatéran) pro θυγατέρα (thugatéra)
<em>daughter</em> (both e.g.&nbsp;in <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/22326">p.babatha.18</a> ll. 34, 38, or
ποδαν instead of πόδα <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1278">bgu.2.380</a> l. 6 or μητέραν
(mētéran) for μητέρα (mētéra) <em>mother</em> <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/34634">p.oxy.1.123</a> l. 22. Also the
masculine word πατήρ (patḗr) <em>father</em> belongs to the same group,
and has occasionally the -n added to the acc.sg. e.g.&nbsp;in <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/33060">p.mich.8.514</a> l. 31. In
papyri, the earliest attestations of the -αν (-an) as acc.sg with the
words <em>mother</em> and <em>father</em> come from the first century
CE. This variation is part of the development where many third
declension words move towards 1st and 2nd declension according to their
gender, see for example <span class="citation" data-cites="dresslerkatsouda2013">Dressler and Katsouda (2013)</span>
discussion for the words in masculine patḗr &gt; πατέρας [pa’teras]
<em>father</em> and feminine mḗtēr &gt; μητέρα [mi’tera] <em>mother</em>
in Modern Greek. <strong>viitteitä lisää, Mayser? mm.</strong></li>
<li>Plural nominative and accusative endings (-ες and -ας respectively)
often transposed (<strong>Vierros forthcoming</strong>)</li>
</ul>
